9. How does GC work
    
    Garbage collection tracks which objects are no longer reachable, and automatically reclaims their memory so you don't get memory leaks like in C.
    
10. young/old/perm generation
    
    Heap memory in JVM is divided into generations because not all objects live the same length of time. Most objects die young — like local variables or temporary objects — while a few live a long time, like caches or static objects. By splitting memory into regions, GC can focus on the area most likely to have garbage instead of scanning the entire heap every time.
    
    New objects start in the Young Generation. GC happens most frequently here, called Minor GC, and most objects get collected here and never leave. Objects that survive enough Minor GCs get promoted to the Old Generation, where GC happens less often — called Major GC or Full GC — but each collection takes longer.
    
    There was also a third region called PermGen, which stored class definitions, method info, and static variables. It was removed in Java 8 and replaced by Metaspace, which moved that metadata outside the heap into native memory, and unlike PermGen it can dynamically expand instead of hitting a fixed size limit.
    
    The one-liner is: generational GC is an optimization — most objects die young and get collected quickly, while the few that survive long enough get promoted and collected less frequently.
    
11. difference types of GC
    
    The main types of Java garbage collectors all come down to one tradeoff: how much do you want to pause your application versus how complex the collector gets.
    The simplest one is Serial GC. It uses a single thread and just freezes your entire application while it cleans up. Easy to understand, but only really usable for tiny apps. Parallel GC does the same thing but throws multiple threads at it, so it's faster overall, but your app still pauses. That's fine for batch jobs where nobody's waiting on a response.
    Then came CMS, which tried to do most of the work while your app was still running, so pauses got much shorter. The downside was it was heavy on CPU and left the heap fragmented over time. It got deprecated in Java 9 and eventually removed in Java 14.
    G1 GC came in to replace it and has been the default since Java 9. Instead of the fixed young and old regions we talked about, it splits the heap into a bunch of small equal-sized chunks and always goes after the ones with the most garbage first. That's literally where the name "Garbage First" comes from. It strikes a good balance between throughput and pause time, which is why most production apps just use this today.
    If you really can't afford pauses, like you're building something that needs extremely low latency, there's ZGC. Introduced in Java 11, it does almost everything concurrently and keeps pauses under 1 millisecond even on massive heaps.
    The overall trend is pretty straightforward. Each new GC traded some simplicity for shorter pauses, going from fully freezing your app to barely pausing it at all.
    

