1. Java modifier scope: public, private, protected, default scope
    
    There are four access levels in Java, and they control how visible a class member is to the outside world.
    
    public means anyone can access it from anywhere. private is the opposite — only the class itself can see it, not even subclasses. protected sits in the middle, allowing access within the same package and also from subclasses even if they're in a different package. Default, which is when you write no modifier at all, allows access within the same package but blocks subclasses that are outside the package.
    
    ```java
    public class Animal {
        public String name;     // anyone can access
        protected int age;      // same package + subclasses
        String type;            // same package only
        private String secret;  // this class only
    }
    ```
    
    One thing worth watching out for: if you don't write any modifier, it is NOT private. It's default, which means the entire package can see it. That trips people up sometimes.
    
