3. how does classloader work
 When you run a Java program, classes are not all loaded into memory at once. The classloader loads them on demand, meaning a class only gets loaded the first time it is actually needed.
The loading process goes through three steps. First it loads the raw bytecode from the .class file into memory. Then it verifies that the bytecode is valid and safe to run. Finally it initializes the class, which means setting up static fields and running any static blocks.
4. Describe the difference between unchecked and checked exceptions in Java.
    
    In Java, exceptions split into two categories based on whether the compiler forces you to handle them.
    
    Checked exceptions are ones the compiler knows might happen, so it requires you to either catch them or declare that your method throws them. They usually represent conditions outside your control, like a file not existing or a network being down.
    
    Unchecked exceptions are subclasses of RuntimeException and the compiler does not force you to handle them. They usually represent bugs in your own code, like accessing a null reference or going out of bounds on an array. The expectation is that you fix the code rather than catch the exception.
    
5. What is the difference between finally, final, and finalize in Java?
    
    These three look similar but have nothing to do with each other.
    final is a keyword that means something cannot be changed. A final variable cannot be reassigned, a final method cannot be overridden by a subclass, and a final class cannot be extended at all. String is a well known example of a final class.
    finally is a block that always runs after a try-catch, regardless of whether an exception was thrown or not. It is typically used to clean up resources like closing a file or database connection.
    
    finalize is a method on the Object class that the garbage collector calls before reclaiming an object's memory. In theory it sounds useful, but in practice it is unreliable because you have no control over when GC runs. It was deprecated in Java 9 and you should not use it in modern code.
    
    One-liner: final locks things down, finally always runs after a try-catch, and finalize is a deprecated GC hook you should forget about.
    
6. Define try-with resource. How can you say that it differs from an ordinary try?
try-with-resources is a version of try that automatically closes resources when the block finishes, whether it exits normally or throws an exception.
    
    The key requirement is that the resource must implement the AutoCloseable interface, which just means it has a close() method. Most standard Java resources like file readers, database connections, and streams already implement it.
    
    The practical difference is that with an ordinary try you have to remember to close the resource yourself in a finally block, and that finally block can itself throw an exception and mask the original one. try-with-resources handles all of that for you cleanly and is always the preferred approach when working with resources in modern Java.
    
7. Define Runtime Exception. Describe it with the help of an example.
    
    A RuntimeException is an unchecked exception that happens during program execution, usually because of a bug in your own code. The compiler does not force you to handle it, and it typically means something in your logic went wrong rather than an external condition failing.
    
    A classic example is NullPointerException. If you try to call a method on an object that was never assigned, Java has nothing to work with and throws it at runtime.
    
    ```java
    String s = null;
    System.out.println(s.length()); 
    
    ```
    
    The compiler had no problem with this code and it compiled fine. The problem only showed up when the program actually ran and tried to call .length() on nothing. That is the defining characteristic of a RuntimeException — it is not a compile time problem, it is a logic problem that only surfaces during execution.
    
8. What is the difference between NoClassDefFoundError and ClassNotFoundException in Java
    
    Both happen when Java cannot find a class, but they occur in different situations.
    
    ClassNotFoundException is a checked exception that happens when you try to load a class dynamically at runtime using something like Class.forName(). The class was simply never on the classpath to begin with, and since you are loading it by name as a string, the compiler had no way to catch it earlier.
    
    NoClassDefFoundError is an error that happens when the class was available at compile time but cannot be found at runtime. This usually means the class existed when you compiled your code but got removed or is missing from the classpath when you actually run it.
    
    The key distinction is timing. ClassNotFoundException means the class was never there. NoClassDefFoundError means it was there when you compiled but disappeared by the time you ran the program.
    
9. Why should we clean up activities such as I/O resources in the finally block?

Because finally is the only block that is guaranteed to run regardless of what happens in the try block.Because finally is the only block that is guaranteed to run regardless of what happens in the try block. Whether the code finishes normally, throws an exception, or even hits a return statement, finally still executes.
If you put your cleanup inside the try block itself, it might never reach that line if an exception gets thrown before it. If you put it in the catch block, it only runs when an exception actually happens, not on the normal path.
    
    ```java
    try {
        FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt");
        
        fr.close(); 
    } catch (IOException e) {
        
    }
    
    FileReader fr = null;
    try {
        fr = new FileReader("file.txt");
    } catch (IOException e) {
       
    } finally {
        if (fr != null) fr.close(); 
    }
    
    ```
    
    I/O resources like file handles, database connections, and network sockets are limited by the operating system. If you do not close them, they stay open and eventually you run out, which causes your program to fail in ways that are hard to debug.
    
    That said, in modern Java the preferred approach is try-with-resources which handles this automatically, so you rarely need to write a finally block for cleanup yourself anymore.
    
10. Describe OutofMemoryError in exception handling.
    
    
     OutOfMemoryError is thrown by the JVM when it runs out of heap memory and cannot allocate space for a new object. 
    The most common cause is creating too many objects without releasing them, so garbage collector runs but cannot free enough memory because everything is still referenced. Another common cause is a memory leak, where objects pile up over time because something keeps holding references to them unintentionally.
    
11. What is Generics in Java? What are the advantages of using Generics?
    
    
    ****Generics allow you to write classes and methods that work with any type while still being type-safe, by letting you specify the type as a parameter.
    
    ```java
    // without generics
    List list = new ArrayList();
    list.add("hello");
    String s = (String) list.get(0); // have to cast manually, can fail at runtime
    
    // with generics
    List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
    list.add("hello");
    String s = list.get(0); // no cast needed, compiler enforces the type
    
    ```
    
    The main advantage is catching type errors at compile time instead of runtime. Without generics, you could accidentally put an Integer into a list meant for Strings and the compiler would not complain. You would only find out when the program crashed. With generics the compiler catches that mistake immediately.
    Generics also eliminate the need for manual casting, which makes code cleaner and less error prone. And they let you write reusable code that works across different types without duplicating logic.
    
    ```java
    // one method works for any type
    public <T> T getFirst(List<T> list) {
        return list.get(0);
    }
    
    getFirst(List.of("a", "b")); // returns String
    getFirst(List.of(1, 2, 3));  // returns Integer
    ```
    
12. How does Generics works in Java ? What is type erasure ?
    
    Generics let you write type-safe code by specifying the type as a parameter, and the compiler uses that information to catch type mismatches at compile time.
    
    Type erasure is what happens after compilation, that is all the generic type information gets stripped out and replaced with Object. So at runtime List<String> and List<Integer> are both just List. The compiler inserts casts automatically where needed, which is why you don't have to write them yourself.
    
    This is also why you can't do new T() or instanceof T inside a generic method — by the time the code runs, T no longer exists.
    
13. What is the difference between List<? extends T> and List <? super T>?
    
    `List<? extends T>` means the list holds T or some subclass of T. You can safely read from it because everything is guaranteed to be at least a T, but you cannot add to it because the compiler does not know the exact subtype.
    
    `List<? super T>` means the list holds T or some superclass of T. You can safely add T objects to it, but reading only gives you Object because the compiler does not know how far up the hierarchy it goes.
    
14. what is Optional class (write a demo code to use ofNullable, orElse, orElseThrow method)
    
    Optional is a wrapper for a value that might be null, so you don't have to write if (x == null) everywhere.
    
    ```java
    import java.util.Optional;
    
    public class OptionalDemo {
    
        static String findUserById(int id) {
            if (id == 1) return "Jocelyn";
            return null;
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            // ofNullable wraps a value that could be null
            Optional<String> found = Optional.ofNullable(findUserById(1));   // present
            Optional<String> missing = Optional.ofNullable(findUserById(99)); // empty
    
            // orElse returns a fallback if empty
            System.out.println(found.orElse("Anonymous"));   // Jocelyn
            System.out.println(missing.orElse("Anonymous")); // Anonymous
    
            // orElseThrow throws if empty
            System.out.println(found.orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Not found"))); // Jocelyn
            System.out.println(missing.orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Not found"))); // throws!
        }
    }
    ```
    
