List<Student> list = new ArrayList<>();

- use stream api to find all the students’ name starting with ‘A’
- use stream api to get the sum of all the students score
- use stream api to find all the students whose sore >= 60
- use stream api to retrieve all students name
- use stream api to count the frequency of each age
- use steam api to count the number of boys girls (groupby, collector.toMap())

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.util.stream.*;

public class StudentDemo {

    static class Student {
        String name;
        int age;
        double score;
        String gender;

        Student(String name, int age, double score, String gender) {
            this.name = name;
            this.age = age;
            this.score = score;
            this.gender = gender;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        List<Student> list = new ArrayList<>();
        list.add(new Student("Alice", 20, 88, "F"));
        list.add(new Student("Amy", 21, 55, "F"));
        list.add(new Student("Bob", 20, 72, "M"));
        list.add(new Student("Charlie", 22, 45, "M"));
        list.add(new Student("Anna", 21, 91, "F"));
        list.add(new Student("David", 22, 63, "M"));

        // 1. names starting with 'A'
        List<String> startsWithA = list.stream()
            .filter(s -> s.name.startsWith("A"))
            .map(s -> s.name)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
        System.out.println("Starts with A: " + startsWithA);
        // [Alice, Amy, Anna]

        // 2. sum of all scores
        double totalScore = list.stream()
            .mapToDouble(s -> s.score)
            .sum();
        System.out.println("Total score: " + totalScore);
        // 414.0

        // 3. students with score >= 60
        List<String> passing = list.stream()
            .filter(s -> s.score >= 60)
            .map(s -> s.name)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
        System.out.println("Passing: " + passing);
        // [Alice, Bob, Anna, David]

        // 4. all student names
        List<String> allNames = list.stream()
            .map(s -> s.name)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
        System.out.println("All names: " + allNames);
        // [Alice, Amy, Bob, Charlie, Anna, David]

        // 5. frequency of each age
        Map<Integer, Long> ageFrequency = list.stream()
            .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(s -> s.age, Collectors.counting()));
        System.out.println("Age frequency: " + ageFrequency);
        // {20=2, 21=2, 22=2}

        // 6. count boys and girls
        Map<String, Long> genderCount = list.stream()
            .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(s -> s.gender, Collectors.counting()));
        System.out.println("Gender count: " + genderCount);
        // {F=3, M=3}
    }
}
```

1. intermediate operation vs terminal operation
Intermediate operations are lazy which means they just describe what to do but nothing actually runs yet. They always return a new Stream so you can keep chaining. Terminal operations trigger the whole pipeline to execute and return a final result, so you can't chain after it.

Terminal operations trigger the entire pipeline to execute and return a final result, not a Stream.

